[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating user code filters**\n\nI'm pondering the complexities of user code filters. If the filter allows `org.osgi.**`, does it mean that user code from the vendor is also included? Actually, if the user code filter excludes everything and includes `org.osgi.**`, then OSGi libraries are treated as user code for recording conditionals. I wonder about the dynamic nature of classes and whether they might treat the test delegate as user code. It seems that if the target isn’t included, metadata might be generated for tests.\n\n**Analyzing class loading and metadata**\n\nI'm trying to figure out if a test class can be reached through a native image when it isn't included in the metadata. If I use `Class.forName`, I wonder if it really requires metadata since the system property is constant at build time, and that’s not clear. The agent captures reflection data but the user-code-filter might not exclude the target class. It could be better if the vendor package starts with `org.osgi.framework.test`. I guess I need to consider the conflicts that might arise with custom classes in the `org.osgi` package and existing library packages.\n\n**Interpreting package structures**\n\nI'm trying to clarify what it means to \"keep tests outside of library's packages.\" Does it imply avoiding the use of `org.osgi.framework`, while `org.osgi.test.vendor` might still be seen as part of the library namespace? It seems that using `org_osgi...` could create its own issues since it won’t be included in the user code filter. I’m considering if the native image could still include reflection config generated by the agent, even for the target test class. I wonder if the user-code-filter just filters the caller code.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0beee1d83eb301440169f72c7abbf4819cb1fa7e84958b76ab\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABp9yyFzJYcB95VXcV5ThkfJyzZyt